Freehold Borough celebrated Veterans Day 2018 by introducing the Lewis Brothers Pavilion at Veterans Park, named after the six Lewis brothers who fought in every branch of the military in World War II.
Private Bigerton "Buddy" Lewis, who served in World War II, placed his hand over his chest while reciting the Pledge of Allegiance.

Veterans, residents and others start taking their seats ahead of the re-dedication of Veterans Park on Nov. 11, 2018. The ceremony commemorated the six Lewis brothers from Freehold Borough who served in World War II.

Bigerton "Buddy" Lewis Jr. placed his hand over his chest as Courtneney Wilds sings the national anthem on Veterans Day, Nov. 11, 2018 at Veterans Park in Freehold Borough. The ceremony commemorated Lewis and his five brothers who served in World War II.

More than 100 people gathered on Nov. 11, 2018, for the re-dedication ceremony at Freehold Borough's Veterans Park. The ceremony commemorated the six Lewis brothers from Freehold Borough who served in World War II.

More than 100 people gathered on Nov. 11, 2018, for the re-dedication ceremony at Freehold Borough's Veterans Park. The ceremony commemorated the six Lewis brothers from Freehold Borough who served in World War II.

Freehold Borough councilwoman Sharon Shutzer, right, announced the guests at the Veterans Park re-dedication ceremony, including (left) Assemblywoman Joann Downey and Lt. Gov. Sheila Oliver. The ceremony commemorated the six Lewis brothers from Freehold Borough who served in World War II.

From left, the Rev. Ronald Sparks, councilwoman Sharon Shutzer, mayor J. Nolans Higgin, town historian Kevin Coyne and youth government alumnus Ricky Coyne watch as public officials deliver remarks during the re-dedication ceremony for Freehold's six Lewis brothers who served in World War II.

Assemblywoman Joann Downey and state Sen. Vin Gopal, both left, present a proclamation to Bigerton "Buddy" Lewis Jr., a private in the 1317th Engineer General Service Regiment during World War II. He was one of six brothers who served in the war.

World Champion Pizza Cup champion Tony Gemignani owns Capo’s in San Francisco’s Little Italy.
The main event at Capo’s is an excellent take on traditional Chicago deep dish pizza. The Old Chicago hides meatballs and sausage under the sauce.
In Amherst, N.Y. since 1959, Bocce Club is known as one of the top spots for Buffalo-style pizza.
Buffalo-style pizza consists of a medium thick crust, with half or whole round pies, sweet sauce, and “cup and char” pepperoni that's thick and crispy.
Celebrity chef and James Beard Award winner Michael Schwartz works the wood-fired oven at his Harry’s Pizzeria in Miami.

Harry's pizzas are mostly sauceless, letting the excellent dough and first-rate toppings speak for themselves. Toppings might feature local Florida rock shrimp with manchego cheese, scallions, cilantro and roasted lemon.

Caption: Sky Zone locations, including Lakewood, Ocean Township and South Plainfield, offer  sensory-friendly hours, during which the music is turned off and distractions are minimized. Go to skyzone.com for info.

For Sensory-Friendly Sundays, exhibits at the Franklin Institute in Philadelphia are modified all day, with trained staff and volunteers on hand. The renowned science museum offers a "try again" rain check if the visit doesn't work out in your first half hour. Discounted admission if arriving between 8 and 9:30 a.m. Sensory maps available for exhibits. For info, go to fi.edu.

Whirlwind engagements and weddings are nothing new in Hollywood. The latest couple: Singer/actor Nick Jonas and "Quantico" actress Priyanka Chopra. They're pictured here at a dinner in Mumbai on November 27, 2018.
They reportedly began dating in May, and rumors Jonas and Chopra's engagement broke on July 27, following reports that Jonas shut down Tiffany & Co. to pick a ring for the Bollywood-bred actress.

In mid-June, reports surfaced that singer Ariana Grande and "Saturday Night Live" cast member Pete Davidson, both 24, had gotten engaged after dating for just a few weeks. Davidson confirmed he'd put a ring on it during a visit to "The Tonight Show."

Reports emerged four months later that Grande and Davidson had split. On November 4, Grande threw shade, releasing a new single right before "SNL" aired. The song, "Thank U, Next," called out her past relationships, including Davidson: "Even almost got married / And for Pete I'm so thankful" before launching into a snappy chorus: "Thank you, next / I'm so (expletive) grateful for my ex."

'Baywatch' star Pamela Anderson and Motley Crue drummer Tommy Lee got married in 1995 just 96 hours after their first date and got each other's names tattooed on their ring fingers instead of exchanging wedding bands.

The couple filed for divorce on two separate occasions: first in 1996, then for good in 1998. They share two sons, but the relationship between the two continues to be tumultuous. After Lee claimed their 21-year-old son Brandon assaulted him in March, Anderson said that he had been trying to arrange an intervention about his father's alcoholism. "(Lee)  is a disaster spinning out of control," she said of her ex. "I will never talk to Tommy again before he is sober and in his right mind."

Ridgewood native Brian Williams, former anchor and managing editor of "NBC Nightly News," was inducted into the New Jersey Hall of Fame in 2014.
Cuban-American salsa performer and Fort Lee resident Celia Cruz was inducted into the New Jersey Hall of Fame in 2013.

East Orange native Dionne Warwick, singer, actress and TV host, was second only to Aretha Franklin as the most-charted female vocalist of all time. She was inducted into the New Jersey Hall of Fame in 2013.

Grammy winner and Englewood resident Dizzy Gillespie, a  jazz trumpet player, bandleader, singer, composer and teacher, pioneered Afro-Cuban jazz. He was inducted into the New Jersey Hall of Fame in 2014.
Long Branch native Dorothy Parker, the author and poet who was a founding member of the Algonquin Round Table, was inducted into the New Jersey Hall of Fame in 2014.
Caldwell native Grover Cleveland was the 22nd and 24th U.S. president. He presided over the dedication of the Statue of Liberty. He was inducted into the New Jersey Hall of Fame in 2013.

Emmy and Golden Globe winning actor  James Gandolfini, a Westwood native raised in Park Ridge,  was best known for his role as Tony Soprano in HBO’s The Sopranos. The Rutgers graduate was inducted into the New Jersey Hall of Fame in 2014.

Jim Florio was a New Jersey governor and represented the state as a congressman. He was noted for his environmental record, including authorship of the Superfund law to clean up the nation’s most polluted sites. He was inducted into the New Jersey Hall of Fame in 2014.

'Jersey Shore' star Mike 'The Situation' Sorrentino was sentenced to eight months in prison on Oct. 5, 2018, after pleading guilty to tax evasion in January. Click through for more celebrities who got in trouble with the IRS over their taxes.

In 2014, "Real Housewives of New Jersey" couple Teresa and Joe Giudice pled guilty to charges of conspiracy to commit fraud along with his failure to pay income tax. Teresa reported to prison first in January 2015, serving 11 months. After her release in December 2015, he reported to prison in March 2016 and is scheduled for release in March 2019. However, he could face deportation before or after his release because he is not a U.S. citizen.
In 2013, Fugees singer and Grammy award-winning solo artist Lauryn Hill was sentenced to three months in federal prison after not paying taxes on approximately $2 million in earnings.
In 2008, actor Nicolas Cage paid $666,000 to settle charges from the IRS claiming he improperly wrote off $3.3 million in personal expenses on his taxes.

In 2007, singer (and Jennifer Lopez's ex-husband) Marc Anthony learned the hard way that his financial managers had not filed his personal income and business taxes from 2000 and 2004. He paid $2.5 million in penalties and back taxes but was not prosecuted.
Credit/Source: Rodrigo Varela, Getty Images for Univision

Caption: Actor Wesley Snipes was sentenced to three years in federal prison after he was convicted in 2008 for evading $7 million in taxes.  He was released on April 2, 2013.

Martha Stewart was forced to pay $220,000 in back taxes and penalties for her home in New York, which she claimed she didn't owe taxes for because she didn't spend much time there. Stewart was later sentenced to prison for insider trading.

Willie Nelson paid $6 million in back taxes after the IRS claimed he owed $16.7 million. He didn't have the funds to pay it all, so Nelson recorded the album "The IRS Tapes: Who'll Buy My Memories?" to help cover the bill.

Caption: Virginia Gov. Ralph Northam, left, gestures as his wife, Pam, listens during a news conference in the Governors Mansion at the Capitol in Richmond, Va., Saturday, Feb. 2, 2019. Northam is under fire for a racial photo that appeared in his college yearbook. (Photo: Steve Helber, AP)
Gov. Ralph Northam's 1984 medical school yearbook shows a photo of a man dressed in blackface and a second person in a KKK robe (Photo: Eastern Virginia Medical School)

Virginia Gov. Ralph Northam, center, and his wife Pam, watch as the casket of fallen Virginia State Trooper Lucas B. Dowell is carried to a waiting tactical vehicle during the funeral at the Chilhowie Christian Church in Chilhowie, Va., Saturday, Feb. 9, 2019. Dowell was killed in the line of duty earlier in the week.

A local newspaper the Richmond Free Press, with a front page featuring top Virginia state officials embroiled in controversies, sits for sale in a newsstand near the Virginia State Capitol, Feb. 9, 2019 in Richmond, Va.  Virginia state politics are in a state of upheaval, with Governor Ralph Northam, State Attorney General Mark Herring, both Democrats, and Republican Senate Majority Leader Tommy Norment involved with past uses associations with blackface and Lt. Governor Justin Fairfax, a Democrat, accused of sexual misconduct by two women.
A Senate page hands out documents to lawmakers, including State Senator Mamie Locke, right, during a Senate session at the Virginia State Capitol, February 8, 2019 in Richmond, Va.
Protestors carry a fake coffin, to symbolize what they call the death of the Democratic Party, toward the Virginia State Capitol, Feb. 7, 2019 in Richmond, Virginia.

Protestors rally against Virginia Governor Ralph Northam outside of the governors mansion in downtown Richmond, Va. on Feb. 4, 2019. Demonstrators are calling for the resignation of Virginia Governor Ralph Northam, after a photo of two people, one dressed as a Klu Klux Klan member and a person in blackface were discovered on his personal page of his college yearbook. Northam said that while he had not appeared in the photo, "many actions that we rightfully recognize as abhorrent today were commonplace" and he was not surprised such material made its way to the yearbook.

Geraldine Mabagos, of Richmond, holds a sign during a protest in Richmond calling for Governor Ralph Northam to resign on Monday Feb. 4, 2019. Northam has rebuffed widespread calls for his resignation after a racist photo surfaced Friday in his 1984 medical school yearbook page.
Credit/Source: Shelby Lum, Richmond Times-Dispatch via AP

Caption: Virginia Gov. Ralph Northam, with his wife Pam at his side, speaks at a press conference in the Executive Mansion at the Capitol in Richmond, Va., Saturday, Feb. 2, 2019. Northam is under fire for a racial photo that appeared in his college yearbook.
Credit/Source: Steve Earley, The Virginian-Pilot via AP

Caption: Members of the media listen to a statement from Virginia Governor Ralph Northam speaks about a racist photo that appeared in his 1984 medical school yearbook, at the Executive Mansion in Richmond, Va. on Feb.2, 2019. Northam is facing pressure to resign from both Republicans and Democrats, after racist medical school yearbook pictures, showing him and another person in racist garb at a party.

Caption:
The kidnapping of the Lindbergh baby: On March 1, 1932, the 1-year-old son of famed pilot Charles Lindbergh was placed in his crib around 7:30 p.m. and was missing two hours later. A nurse found a cryptic note on the windowsill demanding $50,000 for the return of the child. ----
PHOTO: Charles Lindbergh, Jr., son of famed aviator Charles Lindbergh.
Credit/Source: USA TODAY NETWORK NJ archive photo

Caption:
Two months later, a truck driver discovered the remains of Lindbergh Jr. on the side of a highway outside of Trenton. The baby’s skull was crushed. Investigators tracked a $10 bill from the ransom money to a German carpenter named Bruno Richard Hauptmann from the Bronx.----
PHOTO: Hugo Stockburger escorts Bruno Richard Hauptmann.

In February 1935, Hauptmann was found guilty of the murder of Charles Lindenbergh Jr. and was sentenced to death. He was electrocuted in 1936. ----PHOTO: Asbury Park Press coverage from Sept. 21, 1934.
Picture shows Hugo Stockburger escorting Bruno Richard Hauptmann. He would escort him to court and care for him in his cell at the courthouse during the trial in Flemington.
Bruno Richard Hauptmann was convicted and executed for the 1932 murder of Charles Lindbergh, Jr., son of famed aviator Charles Lindbergh.
Credit/Source: USA TODAY NETWORK NJ archive photo

Caption: Charles Lindbergh with his second son Jon several years after the murder of his first son Charles, Jr.
Credit/Source: USA TODAY NETWORK NJ archive photo

Caption: NJ murder: Walk of Death. Howard Unruh lived a relatively quiet life in the Cramer Hill section of Camden before paranoia began to kick in and Unruh suddenly convinced himself that everyone in Cramer Hill despised him and had nothing but bad things to say about him. In September 1949, he loaded his gun and consulted the lists of shopkeepers, neighbors and local townspeople that had scorned him and drifted off to sleep. ----PHOTO: In this Sept. 6, 1949 picture, Howard Unruh, center, is shown with police after his capture in Camden, N.J. Unruh committed a mass murder, gunning down 13 people, in an era when such killings were still rare.

The next day, Unruh ate breakfast with his mother, changed his clothes, grabbed his loaded gun and left the house. His first victim was 27-year-old cobbler John Pilarchik at a nearby shoemaker’s store. Next, Unruh traveled next door to a barbershop and shot 6-year-old Orris Smith who was getting his haircut for the first day of school by barber Clark Hoover, who Unruh shot seconds later. Unruh continued to fire into windows as he walked down the street toward a local drug store where he killed four more people. He killed five people waiting at a red light outside of the store, then two more at a local tailor shop. By the time he stopped at his house to retrieve more ammo, Unruh had killed 13 people and wounded four in a span of 20 minutes.
---- PHOTO: Maurice and Rose Cohen, two of the 13 victims of Unruh’s deadly rampage through East Camden on Sept. 6, 1949, are pictured. Maurice was a druggist and owner of the former River Road Pharmacy at 3200 River Road. His mother, Minnie Cohen, was also killed.

Over 50 police officers surrounded his residence and began bombarding the building with machine guns and pistols. Unruh didn’t budge though, prompting the officers to throw a tear gas cannister through the window. Unruh surrendered minutes later and exited his home through a backdoor. He admitted to the mass murder deemed the “Walk of Death” by local Camden residents and was admitted to the Trenton Psychiatric Hospital. Psychiatrists diagnosed Unruh with paranoid schizophrenia and he was declared unfit to stand trial and was never charged for his horrific crimes. He remained at the hospital for 60 years until his death in October 2009. 

----

PHOTO: Asbury Park Press coverage from September 7, 1949.
Howard Unruh appeared at an annual court hearing in Camden to evaluate his mental condition.

Date: Published 12:12 p.m. ET Jan. 29, 2019 | Updated 7:50 p.m. ET Jan. 30, 2019
Caption: On March 14, "Empire" star Jussie Smollett returned to court to plead not guilty to 16 counts of disorderly conduct and lying to the police about his alleged attack on Jan. 29. The new charges were filed on March 8.

On Feb. 22, Fox announced it was suspending Smollett, one day after the actor was charged with filing a false police report about his alleged Jan. 29 assault. Fox said his character, Jamal Lyon, would be cut out of the final two episodes of Season 5.

"The events of the past few weeks have been incredibly emotional for all of us," said a statement from 20th Century Fox Television attributed to the show's executive producers. "Jussie has been an important member of our 'Empire' family for the past five years and we care about him deeply. While these allegations are very disturbing, we are placing our trust in the legal system as the process plays out. We are also aware of the effects of this process on the cast and crew members who work on our show and to avoid further disruption on set, we have decided to remove the role of Jamal from the final two episodes of the season,” they said, referring to his character, Jamal Lyon, the scion of a recording-industry family.
Smollett is seen in his Feb. 21 booking photo after turning himself into authorities. The evening before, a grand jury indicted him on a felony count of filing a false police report.

Cook County Judge John Fitzgerald Lyke Jr. addresses Smollett in a courtroom sketch from his bond hearing on Feb. 21. Lyke said he was taken aback by the accusations 
even as he told the actor he has the presumption of innocence. “The most vile and despicable part of it, if it’s true, is the noose," said Lyke, who, like Smollett, is black. "That symbol conjures up such evil in this country’s history."

Assistant State's Attorney Risa Lanier briefs reporters after Smollett's bond hearing. Prosecutors say he paid two brothers to stage the assault and stage-managed the whole thing, choosing the location and telling them to put a rope around his neck, pour bleach on him and yell, "This is MAGA country!"

Jussie Smollett leaves Cook County jail after posting bail on Feb. 21. The judge set his bond at $100,000, required the actor to surrender his passport and forbade him from having any contact with the brothers.
Smollett was reportedly expected back on the set of "Empire" hours after leaving the Cook County jail.

In a press conference following his arrest, Chicago Police Superintendent Eddie Johnson said, "First Smollett attempted to gain attention by sending a false letter that relied on racial homophobic and political language. When that didn’t work, Smollett paid $3,500 to stage this attack. The stunt was orchestrated by Smollett because he was dissatisfied with his salary so he concocted a story about being attacked."

On Feb. 22, less than 10 days after interviewing Smollett on "Good Morning America," Robin Roberts called his arrest a "setback for race relations, homophobia, MAGA supporters – the fingers were pointed at them. I cannot think of another case where there's this anger on so many sides, and you can understand why there would be."

Jack Nicholson, April 22.
Hometown: Neptune.
The movie star appeared in Chinatown, The Shining, Terms of Endearment, and many others. And he got his start at Manasquan High School in NJ.

Bill Maher, Jan. 20
Grew up in River Vale, NJ

Buzz Aldrin, Jan. 20.
Hometown: Glen Ridge.
He was the first person to step on the moon. More recently he made headlines for his medical evacuation from the South Pole, as well as his expressions during a Trump speech reinstating the National Space Council.

Kellyanne Conway, Jan. 20.
Hometown: Atco.
She is the White House Advisor for President Trump. She became more well-known during the 2016 presidential campaign, appearing on many news channels and even being parodied by Saturday Night Live.

Alan Alda, Jan. 28.
Lives in Leonia.
Although he was born in New York, Alan Alda resides in the Garden State. The famous actor has starred in M.A.S.H, The Aviator, and Bridge of Spies.

Nathan Lane, Feb. 3.
Hometown: Jersey City.
A star of the stage and screen for decades, Nathan Lane is known for
his comedic, dramatic, and musical performences. He is in The
Lion King, The Birdcage, and Modern
Family.

Aaron Burr, Feb. 6.
Hometown: Newark.
“Aaron Burr, sir!” Vice President Aaron Burr is famous for mortally wounding Alexander Hamilton in a duel in 1804. His story is told in the Broadway musical Hamilton.

Joe Pesci, Feb. 9.
Hometown: Newark.
He has starred in many films over the past few decades, famous for his “funny like a clown” speech in Goodfellas. Other acting credits include My Cousin Vinny and Home Alone.

Judy Blume, Feb. 12.
Hometown: Elizabeth.
She was a part of everyone’s childhood, whether you were a Superfudge fan or more of a Are You There God? lover. The first movie based on her books, Tiger Eyes, came out in 2013.

John Travolta, Feb. 18.
Hometown: Englewood. Whether he stole your heart as Danny Zuko from Grease, or Vincent from Pulp Fiction, or maybe even Edna in Hairspray, there’s no argument Travolta has a long and diverse filmography.

Date: Published 12:02 p.m. ET Jan. 28, 2019 | Updated 2:06 p.m. ET Jan. 29, 2019
Caption: The FBI charged a Brick man with two counts of sexual exploitation of children. (Photo: BlakeDavidTaylor, Getty Images/iStockphoto)

The average police salary tops $100,000 at more than half of the police departments at the Jersey Shore, according to an Asbury Park Press review of pension data. Officers on average earn six-figures in 44 of the 79 law enforcement agencies across Monmouth and Ocean counties.

Asbury Park Press reviewed 2016 New Jersey’s Police and Firemen’s Retirement System data to determine the top paid departments for Monmouth and Ocean counties. All have average salaries over $112,000, which do not include overtime pay
Here's a look at the top 10 departments.

10. Barnegat Police Department in Barnegat Township on April 23, 2013 

Barnegat Police Department is among the top paid police agencies at the Jersey Shore in 2016, according to a review of pension data. Its officers made an average salary of $112,369 last year.

9. Police officers leave Bridle Path in Tinton Falls Tuesday, April 18, 2017, where an armed man was apparently barricaded in a home.
Tinton Falls police officer made an average of $112,578 last year.

8. Freehold Township police officers confer out iPlay America following a distrubance inside the facility, Sunday, March 27, 2016. Freehold Township police officers made an average of $112,706 in 2016

7. A Brick Township police vehicle blocks the entrance to the TD Bank at 2278 Hooper Avenue in the township that was the scene of a robbery Monday, June 19, 2017.

Brick Police Department was among the top paid police agencies at the Jersey Shore, according to a review of pension data. Its officers made an average of $113,609 last year.

6. Police gather along Atlantic Avenue in Point Pleasant Beach Monday, January 16, 2017, where a standoff with police and Ocean County SWAT team members was underway.

Point
Pleasant Beach is one of the more experienced departments when ranked by average
years of service. All but one of the 21 officers in the pension data have
worked for the department for more than 10 years. Last year, they made an average of $113,703.

5. Toms River police officers are shown outside 190  Edgewood Drive in the township Tuesday, March 14, 2017, where a fatal police officer involved shooting occurred.Toms River officer made an average of $144,414 last year.

Date: Published 2:10 p.m. ET Jan. 27, 2019 | Updated 12:49 p.m. ET Jan. 28, 2019
Caption: Twenty-one years ago on Aug. 11, 1997, we were introduced to "The View." A show, where intelligent women discussed their opinions, as well as asked celebrities and political figures the tough questions. Here, we take a look at all of the ladies who have tackled the sometimes-fiery, hot topics, beginning with the OG cast.
Veteran journalist Barbara Walters, seen in 2014, created the series and served as co-host and executive producer.
In March 2015, with her then co-hosts (left to right) Rosie Perez, Nicolle Wallace, Whoopi Goldberg, Joy Behar and Mario Cantone, she celebrated the show's 4,000th episode.

Walters, with then-President Barack Obama in 2010, left her hosting chair in 2014. On her final show, several women in broadcasting paid their respects to the living legend, including Oprah Winfrey, Diane Sawyer and Katie Couric.

Debbie Matenopoulos, second from right, called Walters her colleague for a brief period, as seen in a photo from the show's premiere with (from left), Meredith Vieira, guest Tom Selleck, Joy Behar and Star Jones.

In her early 20s when she landed the gig, Matenopoulos appeared on the show's first two seasons. Since her exit, she has appeared on the show as a guest co-host, as seen in this Nov. 2016 photo with, from left, Vieira, Jones and Behar.
Matenopoulos now serves as host for Hallmark's "Home & Family" talk show.
Star Jones, second from left with Vieira, Behar and Walters, is another member of the original cast.

Jones with, from left Vieira, Bette Midler, Behar and then-co-host Lisa Ling, stunned her counterparts when she announced her exit in 2006 on air, after learning her contract would not be renewed. "I would have loved for Star to have left and not said 'I was fired,' and not make it look like the program was somehow being cruel to her," Walters told The Associated Press shortly after the incident.
She now served as executive producer and writer on "Daytime Divas," a VH1 series about five female cohorts hosting a show called "The Lunch Hour."
